excerpt: A charming seaside area, Fort Kochi is known for its Dutch, Portuguese, and British colonial architecture, and elaborate bamboo fishing nets at Fort Kochi Beach. St. Francis Church was the original burial site of explorer Vasco da Gama. Upscale eateries and chic cafes serve Keralan specialties, and quaint shops sell cotton clothing and handmade souvenirs. Heritage buildings house contemporary art galleries.
detail_description: Fort Kochi, also known as Old Kochi or West Kochi, is a charming seaside area with a rich multicultural history. The Dutch, Portuguese, and British colonial architecture adds to its allure. Visitors can admire the elaborate bamboo fishing nets at Fort Kochi Beach and explore St. Francis Church, the original burial site of explorer Vasco da Gama.
name: Fort Kochi
address: Kochi, Kerala, India

excerpt: Elegant reconstructed 1880s Catholic church originally built by the Portuguese in the 1500s.
detail_description: Santa Cruz Cathedral Basilica in Fort Cochin is a reconstructed 1880s Catholic church with a rich history dating back to the 1500s when it was originally built by the Portuguese. This magnificent structure stands out in dazzling white against the lush greenery of Kochi and boasts two spires that serve as a landmark for both locals and tourists.
name: Santa Cruz Cathedral Basilica, Kochi
address: X67V+W4G, Bastian St, Fort Nagar, Fort Kochi, Kochi, Kerala 682001, India

excerpt: Long stretch of sand popular for walking, swimming, shell collecting & dolphin sightings.
detail_description: Cherai Beach, located on the fringes of Kochi, is a serene stretch of sand known for its natural beauty and tranquility. Visitors can enjoy activities such as walking, swimming, shell collecting, and even spot dolphins in the Arabian Sea. The beach is part of a larger tourist attraction that includes Vypeen Island, Fort Kochi Beach, Kodanad Elephant Training Centre, Mangalavanam Bird Sanctuary, and Marine Drive.
name: Cherai Beach
address: Vypin, Kerala, India

excerpt: Museum of traditional local architecture as well as crafts, folk art & antiques, with a cafe & shop.
detail_description: Kerala Folklore Museum is a unique attraction in Kochi that offers a glimpse into the region's rich cultural heritage. The museum showcases traditional architecture, crafts, folk art, and antiques across three floors. Visitors can also enjoy live performances such as Kathakali dances and traditional martial arts. Additionally, there's a handicraft shop where you can purchase interesting souvenirs.
name: Kerala Folklore Museum
address: 2059C, 26, Pandit Karuppan Rd, near Thevara Ferry Road, Junction, Kochi, Kerala 682013, India

excerpt: Large 19th-century palace complex with an archeological & heritage museum, plus unique parks.
detail_description: The Hill Palace Museum, located in Kochi, Kerala, is a 19th-century palace complex that has been transformed into an archaeological and heritage museum. It was originally the residence of the Maharaja of Cochin and now houses a vast collection of artifacts from the Cochin royal family. The museum boasts an impressive display of oil paintings, murals, swords, manuscripts, and other items used by the royal family.
name: Hill Palace Museum
address: Hill Palace Rd, Irumpanam, Thrippunithura, Ernakulam, Kerala 682301, India

excerpt: Kerala-style palace originally built by the Portuguese in 1555 and later renovated by the Dutch.
detail_description: Mattancherry Palace, also known as Dutch Palace, is a stunning example of Kerala-style architecture with a touch of colonial influence. Originally constructed by the Portuguese in 1555 and later renovated by the Dutch, this palace is located just 10 km from main Ernakulam. The interiors are adorned with beautiful 17th and 18th-century murals depicting scenes from the epics Ramayana and Mahabharata.
name: Mattancherry Palace
address: X755+8P9, Mattancherry, Kochi, Kerala 682002, India

detail_description: The Paradesi Synagogue, located in Mattancherry, Kochi, is a historic site with a rich and tumultuous past. Originally constructed in 1568, it suffered damage from the Portuguese in 1662 but was rebuilt by the Dutch shortly after. The synagogue boasts ornate brass bimah, elegant wooden benches, and intricate hand-painted floor tiles from Canton.
name: Paradesi Synagogue
address: X745+XPW, Synagogue Ln, Jew Town, Kappalandimukku, Mattancherry, Kochi, Kerala 682002, India

excerpt: Marine Drive is a buzzing waterfront district known for the Marine Walkway, popular for evening strolls, and leafy Subhash Bose Park. The modern Rainbow and Kettuvallam bridges offer backwater views, and cruises leave from jetties by the water. Affluent homes and offices fill the area, and shops along Broadway sell jewelry, spices, and local fabrics. Dining ranges from upscale hotel restaurants to no-frills cafes.
detail_description: Marine Drive is a vibrant waterfront area featuring the Marine Walkway and Subhash Bose Park, perfect for leisurely evening walks. The modern Rainbow and Kettuvallam bridges provide scenic backwater views, with cruises departing from nearby jetties. The district is filled with upscale homes, offices, and shops offering jewelry, spices, and local fabrics along Broadway. Dining options range from luxurious hotel restaurants to casual cafes.
name: Marine Drive
address: Kochi, Ernakulam, Kerala, India

excerpt: Views & photo-ops of giant, iconic Chinese style fishing nets suspended from tall bamboo frames.
detail_description: When visiting Fort Kochi in South India, be sure to take in the mesmerizing sight of the Chinese Fishing Nets. These iconic nets, suspended from tall bamboo frames, have been a symbol of Kerala's colonial legacy for over 500 years. They are particularly captivating against the backdrop of the setting sun and are a popular subject for photographs and postcards.
name: Chinese Fishing Nets
address: X69R+9V5, Fort Vypin, Puthuvype, Kochi, Kerala, India

excerpt: Quiet, forested nature refuge in the middle of the city attracting migratory birds & other animals.
detail_description: Mangalavanam Bird Sanctuary, located in Kochi, is a serene nature retreat amidst the urban landscape. This sanctuary serves as a nesting ground for various migratory birds and is an ecologically sensitive area with lush mangroves and a shallow tidal lake connected to the backwaters of Kochi. Surrounded by greenery, it offers breathtaking views of diverse bird species during the migratory season.
name: Mangalavanam Bird Sanctuary
address: High Ct Rd, Marine Drive, Kochi, Ernakulam, Kerala 682031, India

excerpt: Historic Jew Town, the heart of the once-thriving Cochin Jewish community, is known for its old-world charm and 16th-century Paradesi Synagogue. Quaint shops around Synagogue Lane and Jew Town Road sell antiques, carvings, and vintage collectibles, along with Keralan crafts and aromatic spices. Laid-back outdoor cafes and artsy eateries, some in heritage buildings, serve local specialties and Western fare.
detail_description: Jew Town, located in Mattancherry, is a historic area that was once the center of the Cochin Jewish community. The 16th-century Paradesi Synagogue is a major attraction here. The narrow streets are lined with quaint shops selling antiques, carvings, vintage collectibles, and Keralan crafts. Visitors can also find aromatic spices and various home decor items in these small antique shops.
name: Jew Town
address: Anavathil, Kappalandimukku, Mattancherry, Kochi, Kerala 682002, India

excerpt: Founded in 1990, this traditional arts center presents masked Kathakali dance shows & martial arts.
detail_description: GREAT K V Kathakali Centre, established in 1990, is a hub for traditional arts in Fort Kochi. The center showcases captivating masked Kathakali dance performances and martial arts demonstrations. Located near the Santa Cruz Cathedral Basilica, it aims to promote Kerala's classical art forms.
name: GREAT K V Kathakali centre.
address: KB Jacob Rd, Fort Nagar, Fort Kochi, Kochi, Kerala 682001, India

detail_description: If you're a culture and heritage enthusiast, the Indo Portuguese Museum is a must-visit. This museum showcases the rich history of Indian and Portuguese cultures through its architecture and exhibits. Visitors can marvel at items such as silver crosses, wooden crosses, treasures, furniture, and monstrances on display. The museum welcomes visitors every day except Mondays and public holidays, with an affordable entry fee for both Indian citizens and foreigners.
name: Indo Scottish Brand Private Limited
address: W7R6+J4R, Thykavu Road, Karuvelipady, Thoppumpady, Kochi, Kerala 682005, India

detail_description: Discover the rich history and architectural significance of the Paravur Jewish Synagogue, one of the oldest synagogues located on Jew Street in Paravur, Kerala. The synagogue boasts traditional architecture with pillared corridors and teak woods, leading to a prayer room. As part of the Muziris Heritage Plan, it has been meticulously conserved. Visitors can explore its historical significance through guided tours for a nominal fee.
name: Paravur Jewish Synagogue
address: 562C+VCJ, North, Ernakulam, North Paravur, Kerala 683513, India

detail_description: Dutch Palace Pond, also known as Mattancherry Palace, is a two-storied architectural marvel that showcases the traditional style of Kerala. Originally constructed by the Portuguese in 1557 and later renovated by the kings of Kerala, it boasts a blend of European and Indian architectural influences. Situated near the Jewish Synagogue in the Mattencherry neighborhood, this historical site offers insight into colonial history.
name: Dutch Palace Pond
address: Mattancherry, Kochi, Kerala 682002

excerpt: Local history & culture are showcased with sound & light shows, doll collections & art exhibits.
detail_description: Nestled in the vibrant locale of Edapally, near Kalamassery, the Kerala Museum is a treasure trove that beautifully encapsulates the rich tapestry of local history and culture. As you step inside, you're greeted by an impressive statue of Sage Parasurama, revered for his legendary role in shaping Kerala's land.
name: Kerala Museum
address: Metro Pillar 349, Metro Stop, Salem Highway, near Pathadippalam, Koonamthai, Edappally, Kochi, Ernakulam, Kerala 682024, India

detail_description: St. Francis Friary Chapel, also known as St. Francis Church, stands as India's oldest European-built church, with its origins dating back to the 16th century when it was constructed by Portuguese Franciscan friars. Initially made of timber and later reconstructed in stone masonry, the church has undergone various transformations over the centuries. It was restored by the Protestant Dutch in the 18th century and subsequently converted into an Anglican church by the British.
name: St. Francis Friary Chapel
address: W7R6+H7W, Karuvelipady, Thoppumpady, Kochi, Kerala 682002, India

excerpt: This coastal area for swimming & fishing has eateries with water views & a relaxed vibe.
detail_description: Andhakaranazhi Beach, located 30 kilometers from Kochi, is a hidden gem that offers a relaxed and uncommercialized coastal experience. This virgin beach is an extension of the village of Andhakaranazhi and remains relatively unexploited by tourism. The area is known for its picturesque views of the Arabian Sea, pristine sandy shores, coconut groves, and quaint lighthouse. Fishing is a common sight here as it serves as the main occupation for locals.
name: Andhakaranazhi Beach
address: Kerala, India

excerpt: Kochi (also known as Cochin) is a city in southwest India's coastal Kerala state. It has been a port since 1341, when a flood carved out its harbor and opened it to Arab, Chinese and European merchants. Sites reflecting those influences include Fort Kochi, a settlement with tiled colonial bungalows and diverse houses of worship. Cantilevered Chinese fishing nets, typical of Kochi, have been in use for centuries.
detail_description: Kochi, also known as Cochin, is a captivating city located in the coastal state of Kerala in southwest India. With its rich history dating back to 1341 when a flood created its harbor, Kochi has long been a bustling port that attracted traders from Arab, Chinese, and European backgrounds. This vibrant city showcases an eclectic mix of cultures through its colonial architecture in Fort Kochi and various places of worship.
name: Kochi
address: Kerala, India

excerpt: Breezy, lakefront park featuring lush lawns, a children's playground & benches with water views.
detail_description: Subhash Bose Park, also known as Subhash Chandra Bose Park, is a picturesque urban park located in the heart of Kochi, Kerala. Situated adjacent to Marine Drive, it offers stunning views of the Vembanad Lake backwaters and Kochi Harbor.
name: Subhash Bose Park
address: Park Ave, Marine Drive, Kochi, Ernakulam, Kerala 682011, India
